The Atiku Centre, American University of Nigeria (AUN), supported by USAID, launched Teachers Resource Centres (TRCs) to improve educational standard in Adamawa state. The centers, renovated and equipped for optimal results would be supervised by education secretaries of the 11 benefiting councils. AUN President Dawn Dekle, said the TRCs handed over to government is a crucial element in the production of key teaching materials for majority of users located mostly outside the state capital. Prof. Abubakar Abba Tahir who represented Dekle, identified innovation as easily manipulate in interactive learner-centered classroom activities. “The AUN, will continue to collaborate and upscale the educational needs of communities in more ways”. Dr Grace Malgwi, Deputy Chief of Party in her remarks said, operational guideline was developed detailed for the purpose by the Strengthening Education in the Northeast (SENSE). The guidelines is to ensure uniformity and excellence in the way the centers are run across the councils. Wulbina Jackson, Commissioner of Education, urged for the sustenance of the program to cover the entire states. According to her, government would continue support enhancing education standard and scaling up synergy for the betterment of education sector. The centers were located in Fufore, Ganye, Guyuk, Hong, Michika, Mubi-South, Numan Shelleng, Song Toungo and Yola-North councils in Adamawa state. 